t_adaptations_s2: She is in a wheelchair full time. I received a special needs car seat from Medicaid that I hated but was the best that would be paid for by medicaid, it cost upwards of $10,000. It did not have a "bucket seat" that leaned back like the standard carseats so when she sat up in it her head was dangling outside of the head pads since she has very little head control. It also used the actual car seatbelt to secure the seat into place which had to go across her body it was not made to secure behind the seat, it worked well however the path for the seatbelt made it so that it was pressing right up against her neck and continually left a deep red mark on her neck on one side for hours. I went back to the seating clinic 2 times to try to fix these issues, I received a cushion to tilt the seat back to try to fix the head issue but it barely did anything at all so i had to start putting her in a soft collar to keep her head upright which she absolutely hated. The seating clinic told me they could not legally tell me that it was safe to put a cover over the seat belt to keep her neck from getting a pressure mark so that problem remained unsolved. I eventually found a standard carseat that would work for her up to 65 pounds and also accommodate her height (most kids that are 65 pounds are not close to 4' tall that was the main problem with finding one). That one cost $285 and she just recently grew out of that one. My mom, god bless her, paid $1800 for a tailored made special needs car seat that works perfectly for her and she can use for the rest of her life as it will grow with her so I finally feel like she is safe in the car.
t_difficulties_text_s2: There are not always handicap spots open so when that happens it makes it incredibly difficult to get her in and out of the car to go into the appointment. If there is not an available handicap spot i have to put her wheelchair behind my trunk and then both get her out and squeeze myself and all 73 pounds of her between my car and the car next to me to then strap her into her wheelchair behind the car and keep my fingers crossed that everyone driving in the parking lot isn't looking at their phone and actually paying attention and doesnt hit us because we are actually in the lane of traffic.
t_advice_s2: I really liked having a car seat specialist at [HospitalName] that was available to be called while my child was inpatient in the hospital to come look at my carseats and make sure she was safe. She was able to help me install every new carseat that i ever got, show me how to use them and would stay as i strapped her in myself and make sure I was doing everything right and that my daughter was safe. I would suggest an in-person visit containing all these things to every special medical needs child as it is so much easier than trying to figure everything out on your own and possibly screwing it up. I see people post videos ALL the time of their kids while driving in the car and their kids are not secured properly (mainly that the chest clip is by their stomach and not level to their armpits) this is so unsafe and so easily fixable if people just knew how to properly restrain their kids.
